Negative or positive, dimensionless number with decimal representation to allow representation of non-integer values. In theory, floating point values have a range from (-inf, inf) but in practice, due to a particular representation, this range may be limited. All floating point representations should be able to represent both positive and negative infinity.

Dimensionless, negative or positive whole number or zero. For the purposes of ISA, generic integers are required to hold value in the range (-2^32, 2^32). Specializations of the integer, as defined in the Simple Types, may be able to hold values in the range [0, 2^64), but values in this range are not generally needed in practice.

Every event generated by a component must provide an integer key that allows that event to be updated and referred to at a later point. Event IDs are required to be unique only within the component that's generating them and within a reasonable timeframe after the event is generated. Event IDs are not expected to be sufficient to uniquely identify a single event throughout all time. For this purpose, the combination of source component ID, timestamp, and event ID are used.

Symbol Identification Coding Scheme (SIDC) is a 15-character alphanumeric identifier that provides the information necessary to display or transmit a tactical symbol between MIL-STD-2525 compliant systems.

Universal Component Identifier. This is a string that uniquely identifies a specific component. This is the string that will always be used to refer to this specific component. This can be an assigned number from a logistics group (such as the Army's URNs) or can be a vendor-assigned string (such as combining the manufacturer, model, and serial number in a unique way).

Uniform Resource Locator (URL) is a string used to specify where a resource is located on a network and the mechanism for retrieving it. URLs must comply with IETF RFC 1738, which governs the proper form and syntax of the URL.

The Resource Type is used to define a resource. The valid values are based off of the Internet media type standard defined by IANA with additional values that are applicable to ISA. The enumeration lists common types, but it is possible to use types that are not defined within the enumeration. The official IANA Media Type registry should be consulted when creating a custom resource type.

All rotations in the data model are expressed as a series of three angles: yaw, pitch, and roll. These rotations are applied sequentially, establishing new axes of rotation after each individual rotation is finished. Positive rotations are defined as clockwise around the axis, from the perspective of the origin. Rotation is first applied through the z-axis (yaw), followed by rotation through the newly established y'-axis (pitch) and finally ending with a rotation through the newly established x''- axis (roll).

Relative velocity in each of the three rotational axes. Each element of this object is a percentage instance. These three percentages are the pitch rate, roll rate, and yaw rate given as a percentage of maximum speed, corresponding to the three fields in the orientation.

Three angular velocities representing the rotational velocity about each of the three rotational axes. Each element of this object is an angular velocity instance. These three angular velocities are the pitch rate, roll rate, and yaw rate, corresponding to the three fields in the orientation.

For the purpose of translations, the Data Model uses a right-forward-down reference frame. In general, the precise meaning of forward, right, and down are up to the individual component to define, with the expectation that it will be consistent for all instances of the component, and if a component has a directional aspect to its view area or detection area, that direction should corespond to the concept of forward.
